	<li id="comment-20039" class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1">
		<article id="div-comment-20039" class="comment-body">
			<footer class="comment-meta">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
					<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/bed8f55e298eafb47174cb0d9b8bea27?s=75&amp;d=retro&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-75 photo' height='75' width='75' />					<cite class="fn">cppthis</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>				</div><!-- .comment-author -->

				<div class="comment-metadata">
					<a href="http://www.technollama.co.uk/we-need-decentralized-cryptocurrencies-we-just-dont-need-bitcoin/comment-page-1#comment-20039">
						<time datetime="2013-04-21T15:24:00+00:00">
							April 21, 2013 at 3:24 pm						</time>
					</a>
									</div><!-- .comment-metadata -->

							</footer><!-- .comment-meta -->

			<div class="comment-content">
				<p>My thoughts, as a hardcore misanthropic libertarian who&#039;s followed BTC for a while but never took the plunge: </p>
<p>Transparency: I agree that there&#039;s a lot of unanswered questions about just exactly who the early adopters and what, if any, their agenda might be.  For a supposedly open and libertarian-friendly alternative currency there&#039;s an awful lot of question marks that shouldn&#039;t be there.  If, as has been alleged by many, there is a cabal of early adopters tweaking the market to enrich themselves and their friends it&#039;s no better than a traditional currency whose central bank tweaks the value to enrich itself and its friends. </p>
<p>Failsafes: I see a Bitcoin is similar to a gold coin, except that (supposedly) some legitimate merchants will accept it as payment.  If you lose your Bitcoin you&#039;re hosed, but if you lose your gold coin you&#039;re hosed too.  An interesting point to ponder is what BTC might look like 10 or 20 years from now if the global pool of coins slowly bleeds out.  If you accidentally your gold coin it will turn up in someone&#039;s hands at some point, but your Bitcoin is just vanished in the ether.  And let&#039;s be honest here, a lot of USDs could vanish overnight too if a rogue government or terrorist organization with significant technological and military resources decided to nuke a major bank. </p>
<p>Regulation: I&#039;d have to disagree with you here, maybe if there was some community-based regulation sort of like how Linux experts police the repositories then maybe, but the last thing BTC needs is some government bureaucrats getting involved.  Government bureaucrats and their symbiotic relationship with corrupt financial institutions are precisely the reason so many people are looking at non USD based assets, even stuff as daft as BTC (and let&#039;s be honest, when taken at face value BTC *is* pretty daft). </p>
<p>Deflation: I&#039;m not sure if this is good or bad, but I do think that there being a hard limit to the total number of available BTC is a recipe for disaster in the long term.  The real valuation problem with BTC is that since it&#039;s not widely accepted as a real currency there&#039;s few reasons not to hoard it.  Also, BTC is (currently) linked closely to world currencies and the game could change drastically if and when those currencies become unstable.  To put it another way, if global commerce loses faith in the US dollar it won&#039;t really matter if you bought your computer with X dollars, Y yuan, or Z Bitcoins because the value is now intrinsic to the computer, not the ephemeral currency used to buy it. </p>
<p>Centralization: Yup, the fact that Gox is so predominant really undermines the core concept of an alt currency.  A good peer to peer cryptocurrency needs to exist outside of any single institution but right now if you want to control BTC you just need to control Gox and the rest will follow.  Hence why it&#039;s such a popular target for attacks; a lot of analysts have suggested that a lot of the Gox attacks aren&#039;t actually aimed at disrupting Gox itself but at causing a run on the exchanges so that the attackers can do a big flip with their secret accounts.  Hans Gruber sends his regards. </p>
<p>Instability: Again, the problem is a combination of lack of acceptance and comparison to &quot;stable&quot; fiat currencies.  The BTC market, like silver, is dominated by amateur speculators with a few Soros-style large volume market manipulators thrown in for good measure.  The USD&#039;s ubiquity as a unit of measure is, historically speaking, the exception rather than the rule and it&#039;s only a matter of time before Camelot falls.  Of course, when that happens there will be a resurgence in the use of barter and intrinsic-value coinage so BTC may not actually benefit from this. </p>
<p>Security: This is definitely a major weakness of BTC though I&#039;m not sure if any cryptocurrency can really get around this without selling out to one or more governments and thus invalidating its purpose.  Security is based around fear of reprisal, i.e. if you steal a bunch of pounds sterling the SAS will come to your house and shoot you in the head with an SA80.   Steal yuan and PLA specops will send you to the gulag.   This model doesn&#039;t translate well to an anonymous cryptocurrency on a number of levels. </p>
<p>Politics: I&#039;d agree that BTC is a bit too wrapped up in technolibertarian politics for its own good but can you really blame them?  Lest we forget, this crash was preceded by a major spike when the Cypriot government decided it would skip the foreplay and just start seizing people&#039;s assets to prop up the EU because hey, we&#039;re the government, we have lots of guns, and we can do whatever we want as long as we don&#039;t piss off someone with more guns than us.  While central-bank fiat currency won&#039;t cease to exist there&#039;s simply no way the current spending levels can be sustained and the late 2010s and early 2020s are going to bring about a radical redefinition of wealth when said banks finally drown in their own sea of red ink. </p>
<p>All in all I think BTC is an interesting experiment in a financial system that&#039;s not tied to a government but it does have some flaws that need to be addressed in order to be taken seriously.  It&#039;s a good proof of concept, but cryptocurrency isn&#039;t ready for wide release just yet. </p>
			</div><!-- .comment-content -->

