			<div class="comment-content">
				<p>Just as a matter of law, your opinion that Directive 2009/110 would apply to Bitcoin may be in need of some consideration. </p>
<p>To qualify as e-money, Bitcoin would need to have an issuer, and Bitcoins would need to give holders a &quot;claim&quot; against such issuer. Who is the &quot;issuer&quot; of Bitcoin? Keep in mind that under Article 1 of the Directive the issuer would need to be a legal person. </p>
<p>It is a different question if someone operating a Bitcoin exchange needs a permit. I think that at least for German law they do need one. And I also think that is a good thing, since it helps gaining legitimacy and trust. </p>
			</div><!-- .comment-content -->

