	<li id="comment-20126" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 parent">
		<article id="div-comment-20126" class="comment-body">
			<footer class="comment-meta">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
					<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/fe14b61a46f729b95e19eb7c8f14315b?s=75&amp;d=retro&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-75 photo' height='75' width='75' />					<cite class="fn">pau</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>				</div><!-- .comment-author -->

				<div class="comment-metadata">
					<a href="http://www.technollama.co.uk/we-need-decentralized-cryptocurrencies-we-just-dont-need-bitcoin/comment-page-1#comment-20126">
						<time datetime="2013-07-14T13:55:13+00:00">
							July 14, 2013 at 1:55 pm						</time>
					</a>
									</div><!-- .comment-metadata -->

							</footer><!-- .comment-meta -->

			<div class="comment-content">
				<p>A couple of minor corrections:</p>
<p>&#8220;the problem with deflation is that it encourages hoarding, in which case the currency is not being used as intended, namely to exchange it for goods and services. If everyone kept their money and hid it under the mattress, then the economy would enter into a downward spiral as businesses would have no revenue, so they could not employ people. Moderate inflation is desired in a healthy economy because it encourages investment and spending&#8221;</p>
<p>This isn&#8217;t quite true. Deflation caused by hoarding does not lead to a downward spiral. There are no historical examples of this. In fact, there is no historical correlation between deflation and depressions, with the exception of the Great Depression (and there was a lot of other stuff going on there to explain that). It is ridiculous to assume that just because a currency will be more valuable in the future that nobody will spend it. Do you never buy a computer because 1 year from now you could buy it for less (or you could buy a better one)? Of course not. Some people will wait, but some won&#8217;t. And the more people who wait the more the value of each coin increases. This means that the &#8220;cost&#8221; of holding goes up. And because the value goes up, it doesn&#8217;t take as many bitcoins to cover the same transactions. While businesses may see their nominal revenues decrease, real revenues won&#8217;t. The only way it starts to affect real revenue is when the change is large as unpredictable. Large, unpredictable deflations have happened historically with some fractional reserve banks, central banks, and fiat-like currencies that were intentionally deflated. It may have happened with some wars. However, such a deflation hasn&#8217;t ever occurred as a result of real GDP growing while the actual supply of the currencies stayed relatively fixed.<br />
In addition, the slow deflation that bitcoin would see if it were a major currency would not only encourage hoarding. It would also encourage saving (AKA lending). Of course governments could intervene to prevent or limit a market in bitcoin-denominated loans. But if I lend someone else my bitcoins, then I&#8217;ll get the benefit of deflation as well as a bit of interest. And those bitcoins will still be spent, so there won&#8217;t be any extra deflation because of my savings. (Of course, the steady, predictable deflation would lead to interest rates being lower than it might otherwise be. This would compensate the borrowers for having to repay their loans in higher value bitcoins in the future.)</p>
<p>&#8220;The leftist anarchic fear and loathing of government is shared by the Randian libertarian branches on the right.&#8221;<br />
It would probably be more accurate to call them &#8220;Rothbardian libertarians.&#8221; Rand was not an anarchist. Most libertarian anarchists look more towards Rothbard, who was one of the first major anarcho-capitalists.</p>
			</div><!-- .comment-content -->

			<div class="reply">
				<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/we-need-decentralized-cryptocurrencies-we-just-dont-need-bitcoin/comment-page-1?replytocom=20126#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-20126", "20126", "respond", "6100")'>Reply</a>			</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- .comment-body -->

	<ul class="children">

	<li id="comment-20127" class="comment even depth-2">
		<article id="div-comment-20127" class="comment-body">
			<footer class="comment-meta">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
					<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/112209a23bfac38deafa07a188c9be49?s=75&amp;d=retro&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-75 photo' height='75' width='75' />					<cite class="fn"><a href="http://www.technollama.co.uk"   rel='external nofollow' class='url'>technollama</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>				</div><!-- .comment-author -->

				<div class="comment-metadata">
					<a href="http://www.technollama.co.uk/we-need-decentralized-cryptocurrencies-we-just-dont-need-bitcoin/comment-page-1#comment-20127">
						<time datetime="2013-07-15T03:35:55+00:00">
							July 15, 2013 at 3:35 am						</time>
					</a>
									</div><!-- .comment-metadata -->

							</footer><!-- .comment-meta -->

			<div class="comment-content">
				<p>@pauThanks for the interesting points. </p>
<p>&#8220;Deflation caused by hoarding does not lead to a downward spiral.&#8221;<br />
The most recent episodes of deflation have been followed by stagnation due to lack of consumer spending (Hong Kong and Japan). <br />
 &#8220;Do you never buy a computer because 1 year from now you could buy<br />
it for less (or you could buy a better one)? Of course not. Some people<br />
will wait, but some won&#8217;t. And the more people who wait the more the<br />
value of each coin increases. This means that the &#8220;cost&#8221; of holding goes<br />
 up.&#8221;<br />
I would exclude the deflationary effect caused by technological advance from monetary discussion as it responds to different variables. It has become a fact that technical consumer goods improve all the time, so consumers can make decisions based on that knowledge that are not attached to actual price. Personally, I do wait all the time, I never buy first generation anything. But when I do have to buy, I know in advance that in a year my product will be outdated, but I still buy products based on need. <br />
With monetary deflation, the waiting decision would be enhanced, with fewer people deciding to buy some types of consumer goods, in favour of hoarding and waiting to see if the market shifts. As far as I can tell, Bitcoin continues to respond to the expectation that the price will go up, as it seems that the number of people using it to trade in goods and services continues to be minimal. Good for Bitcoin as speculation, bad for BTC as a currency. <br />
 &#8220;It would probably be more accurate to call them &#8220;Rothbardian<br />
libertarians.&#8221; Rand was not an anarchist. Most libertarian anarchists<br />
look more towards Rothbard, who was one of the first major<br />
anarcho-capitalists.&#8221;<br />
I wasn&#8217;t thinking of anarcho-capitalists or Rothbardian libertarians when I wrote. I think that anarcho-capitalists are a very tiny minority.I admit that this is highly contentious, as I&#8217;m not aware of any survey that identifies percentages of belief, in my own anecdotal experience I&#8217;d say that the vast majority of libertarians I&#8217;ve encountered are of the Randian variety, and I&#8217;ve only encountered a handful of anarcho-capitalists. Traditional leftist anarchists are also more numerous in my experience, so I used both groups on purpose.<br />
More importantly, BTC forums and discussions are filled with Randian Libertarians, if I had a Satoshi for every &#8220;unbound&#8221; &#8220;Atlas&#8221; &#8220;Shrug&#8221; and &#8220;JOhGalt&#8221; that I&#8217;ve seen, I&#8217;d be a BTC millionaire <img src="http://www.technollama.co.uk/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=";)" class="wp-smiley" /> </p>
			</div><!-- .comment-content -->

			<div class="reply">
